### Flora and Fauna

Sulawesi occupies a unique biogeographical position within [Wallacea](/Wallacea), a transitional zone where species from both the [Indomalayan](/Indomalayan_realm) and [Australasian](/Australasian_realm) realms meet. This unique location has resulted in a distinctive mix of flora and fauna, with a high degree of [endemism](/Endemism).

The island is home to one native eucalypt, *[Eucalyptus deglupta](/Eucalyptus_deglupta)*, known for its strikingly colorful bark. Sulawesi hosts eight [national parks](/List_of_national_parks_of_Indonesia), four of which are primarily marine. The largest terrestrial parks are [Bogani Nani Wartabone National Park](/Bogani_Nani_Wartabone_National_Park) and [Lore Lindu National Park](/Lore_Lindu_National_Park). [Bunaken National Park](/Bunaken_National_Park), renowned for its vibrant coral ecosystems, has been recognized as a potential UNESCO [World Heritage Site](/World_Heritage_Site). The waters off the northern tip of Sulawesi are considered a hotspot of marine biodiversity within the [Coral Triangle](/Coral_Triangle).

#### Mammals

The mammalian fauna of Sulawesi tells a story of ancient migrations and evolutionary adaptations. During the [Pleistocene epoch](/Pleistocene_epoch), the island was inhabited by a dwarf elephant and a dwarf form of [Stegodon](/Stegodon), later replaced by larger relatives. A giant [suid](/Suidae), *[Celebochoerus](/Celebochoerus)*, also once roamed the island. It is believed that many migrants arrived via the [Philippines](/Philippines), with Sulawesi serving as a stepping stone to [Flores](/Flores). A significant faunal turnover occurred during the [Pleistocene epoch](/Pleistocene_epoch), with the displacement of indigenous tarsiers by later arrivals and the replacement of *[Celebochoerus](/Celebochoerus)* by other herbivores like the [babirusa](/Babirusa), [anoa](/Anoa), and [Celebes warty pig](/Celebes_warty_pig).

Sulawesi is a remarkable center of mammalian endemism, with 62% of its 127 native mammalian species found nowhere else. The most striking endemics include the two species of [anoa](/Anoa), or dwarf buffalo, and the aberrant pigs, the warty pig and various species of babirusa. The island's sole native [carnivoran](/Carnivora) is the [Sulawesi palm civet](/Sulawesi_palm_civet), though introduced species like the [Asian palm civet](/Asian_palm_civet) and [Malayan civet](/Malayan_civet) are also present.

The primate fauna is particularly notable, featuring several species of nocturnal [tarsiers](/Tarsier), including *[T. fuscus](/Tarsius_fuscus)*, [Dian's tarsier](/Dian%27s_tarsier), [Gursky's spectral tarsier](/Gursky%27s_spectral_tarsier), [Jatna's tarsier](/Jatna%27s_tarsier), [Wallace's tarsier](/Wallace%27s_tarsier), the [Lariang tarsier](/Lariang_tarsier), and the [pygmy tarsier](/Pygmy_tarsier). Diurnal [macaques](/Macaque) are also present, including [Heck's macaque](/Heck%27s_macaque), the [booted macaque](/Booted_macaque), the [crested black macaque](/Celebes_crested_macaque), the [Gorontalo macaque](/Gorontalo_macaque), the [moor macaque](/Moor_macaque), and the [Tonkean macaque](/Tonkean_macaque).

While most of Sulawesi's mammals are placental and have Asian relatives, the island also hosts several species of [cuscus](/Cuscus), arboreal [marsupials](/Marsupials) of Australasian origin, such as *[Ailurops ursinus](/Ailurops_ursinus)* and *[Strigocuscus celebensis](/Strigocuscus_celebensis)*.

The island is a hotspot for endemic [rodent](/Rodent) genera. Within the [Muridae](/Muridae) family, genera like *[Bunomys](/Bunomys)*, *[Echiothrix](/Echiothrix)*, *[Margaretamys](/Margaretamys)*, *[Taeromys](/Taeromys)*, and *[Tateomys](/Tateomys)* are endemic to Sulawesi and its immediate surroundings. Single-species genera such as *[Eropeplus](/Eropeplus)*, *[Hyorhinomys](/Hyorhinomys)*, *[Melasmothrix](/Melasmothrix)*, *[Paucidentomys](/Paucidentomys)*, *[Paruromys](/Paruromys)*, *[Sommeromys](/Sommeromys)*, and the semi-aquatic *[Waiomys](/Waiomys)* also highlight the island's unique rodent diversity. Sulawesi's [sciurids](/Sciuridae) (squirrels) are equally distinctive, with all nine species belonging to three endemic genera: *[Hyosciurus](/Hyosciurus)*, *[Prosciurillus](/Prosciurillus)*, and *[Rubrisciurus](/Rubrisciurus)*.

Of the more than 20 bat species found on Sulawesi, a significant portion are endemic, including *[Rhinolophus tatar](/Rhinolophus_tatar)*, *[Scotophilus celebensis](/Scotophilus_celebensis)*, and several species of [megabats](/Megabat).

Endemic shrews, such as the [Sulawesi shrew](/Sulawesi_shrew), [Sulawesi tiny shrew](/Sulawesi_tiny_shrew), and [Sulawesi white-handed shrew](/Sulawesi_white-handed_shrew), also inhabit the island. Interestingly, Sulawesi lacks gliding mammals, positioning it geographically between Borneo, which has [colugos](/Sunda_flying_lemur) and [flying squirrels](/Flying_squirrel), and Halmahera, home to [sugar gliders](/Sugar_glider).

#### Birds

While many of Sulawesi's bird species are shared with neighboring islands like [Borneo](/Borneo), 31% are endemic. A notable endemic species is the [maleo](/Maleo), a ground-dwelling, chicken-sized [megapode](/Megapode) that utilizes the volcanic heat of vents to incubate its eggs. Conservation efforts, such as the Alliance for Tompotika Conservation, are underway to protect the nesting grounds of this unique bird. Other endemic avian species include the flightless [snoring rail](/Snoring_rail), the [fiery-browed starling](/Fiery-browed_starling), the [Sulawesi masked owl](/Sulawesi_masked_owl), the [Sulawesi myna](/Sulawesi_myna), the [satanic nightjar](/Satanic_nightjar), and the [grosbeak starling](/Grosbeak_starling). Sulawesi is home to approximately 350 known bird species.

#### Reptiles

The larger reptiles found on Sulawesi are not endemic and include species such as the [reticulated python](/Reticulated_python), [Burmese python](/Burmese_python), [Pacific ground boa](/Pacific_ground_boa), [king cobra](/King_cobra), [water monitor](/Water_monitor), [sailfin lizard](/Hydrosaurus_amboinensis), [saltwater crocodile](/Saltwater_crocodile), and [green sea turtle](/Green_sea_turtle). An extinct giant [tortoise](/Tortoise), *[Megalochelys atlas](/Megalochelys_atlas)*, once inhabited the island but disappeared by 840,000 years ago, possibly due to the arrival of [Homo erectus](/Homo_erectus). Evidence suggests that [komodo dragons](/Komodo_dragon) or similar large lizards may have also been present, acting as apex predators.

The smaller snake fauna includes non-endemic species like the gliding snake *[Chrysopelea paradisi](/Chrysopelea_paradisi)*, alongside endemic species such as various *[Calamaria](/Calamaria)* species, *[Cyclotyphlops](/Cyclotyphlops)*, *[Enhydris matannensis](/Enhydris_matannensis)*, *[Ptyas dipsas](/Ptyas_dipsas)*, *[Rabdion grovesi](/Rabdion_grovesi)*, *[Tropidolaemus laticinctus](/Tropidolaemus_laticinctus)*, and *[Typhlops conradi](/Typhlops_conradi)*. Similarly, smaller lizards include non-endemic species like *[Bronchocela jubata](/Bronchocela_jubata)*, *[Dibamus novaeguineae](/Dibamus_novaeguineae)*, and *[Gekko smithii](/Gekko_smithii)*, as well as endemic species such as *[Lipinia infralineolata](/Lipinia_infralineolata)* and *[Gekko iskandari](/Gekko_iskandari)*.

Sulawesi also hosts several species of freshwater turtles, two of which are endemic: *[Forsten's tortoise](/Forsten%27s_tortoise)* and the [Sulawesi forest turtle](/Sulawesi_forest_turtle). These likely evolved from mainland Asian species that dispersed from the exposed [Sundaland](/Sundaland) subcontinent during the [Pleistocene epoch](/Pleistocene_epoch). The island also supports the non-endemic [Malayan box turtle](/Malayan_box_turtle) and the [Asiatic softshell turtle](/Asiatic_softshell_turtle).

#### Amphibians

The amphibian fauna of Sulawesi includes numerous endemic frogs, such as *[Hylarana celebensis](/Hylarana_celebensis)*, *[H. macrops](/Hylarana_macrops)*, *[H. mocquardi](/Hylarana_mocquardi)*, *[Ingerophrynus celebensis](/Ingerophrynus_celebensis)*, *[Limnonectes arathooni](/Limnonectes_arathooni)*, *[L. larvaepartus](/Limnonectes_larvaepartus)*, *[L. microtympanum](/Limnonectes_microtympanum)*, *[Occidozyga celebensis](/Occidozyga_celebensis)*, *[O. semipalmata](/Occidozyga_semipalmata)*, and *[O. tompotika](/Occidozyga_tompotika)*. The island is also home to endemic "flying frogs" like *[Rhacophorus edentulus](/Rhacophorus_edentulus)* and *[R. georgii](/Rhacophorus_georgii)*.

#### Freshwater Fish

Sulawesi is a treasure trove of freshwater fish diversity, boasting over 70 species, with more than 55 being endemic. A particularly remarkable group is the genus *[Nomorhamphus](/Nomorhamphus)*, a species flock of viviparous halfbeaks comprising 12 species found exclusively on Sulawesi. Other endemic fish families include ricefishes, gobies (*[Glossogobius](/Glossogobius)* and *[Mugilogobius](/Mugilogobius)*), and the [Telmatherinid](/Telmatherinidae) sail-fin silversides, which are largely confined to the Malili Lake system. The unique endemic *[Lagusia micracanthus](/Lagusia_micracanthus)*, the sole member of its genus and one of the smallest grunters, inhabits rivers in South Sulawesi. The [gudgeon](/Eleotridae) *[Bostrychus microphthalmus](/Bostrychus_microphthalmus)*, found in the Maros Karst, is the only described species of [cave-adapted fish](/Cavefish) from Sulawesi, though an undescribed species from the same region is also known.

#### Freshwater Crustaceans and Snails

Sulawesi's freshwater ecosystems are home to a remarkable array of endemic crustaceans. Numerous species of *[Caridina](/Caridina)* freshwater shrimp and parathelphusid freshwater crabs, belonging to genera such as *[Migmathelphusa](/Migmathelphusa)*, Nautilothelphusa, *[Parathelphusa](/Parathelphusa)*, *[Sundathelphusa](/Sundathelphusa)*, and *[Syntripsa](/Syntripsa)*, are found only on the island. Many of these species are popular in the aquarium trade, but their restriction to specific lake systems makes them vulnerable to habitat loss and overexploitation. The Maros Karst region is particularly rich in endemic cave-adapted crustaceans, including *[Cancrocaeca xenomorpha](/Cancrocaeca_xenomorpha)*, described as the "most highly cave-adapted species of crab known in the world."

The genus *[Tylomelania](/Tylomelania)* of [freshwater snails](/Freshwater_snail) is also endemic to Sulawesi, with most species concentrated in the ancient lakes of Poso and Malili.

#### Insects

The island's insect diversity includes endemic species like the flightless [weevil](/Weevil) *Trigonopterus selayarensis*.

#### Miscellaneous

The waters surrounding Sulawesi are home to fascinating marine life, including the [Indonesian coelacanth](/Indonesian_coelacanth) and the highly adaptable [mimic octopus](/Mimic_octopus).

### Conservation

Sulawesi's unique biodiversity faces significant threats. A recent Ecoregional Conservation Assessment, coordinated by [The Nature Conservancy](/The_Nature_Conservancy), highlighted the urgent need for conservation action. Despite detailed reports and distribution of conservation priorities, the island's natural habitats are under immense pressure.

The lowland forests, which are naturally limited in extent due to the island's dramatic topography, have been extensively cleared for logging and large-scale agricultural projects. This deforestation has pushed many of Sulawesi's endemic species towards endangerment. Furthermore, 99% of the island's wetlands have been lost or degraded. Other critical threats include hunting for bushmeat and mining activities.

Sulawesi boasts six national parks and nineteen nature reserves, alongside three marine protected areas. However, many of these protected areas are compromised by ongoing logging, mining, and agricultural encroachment.

The islands of Pepaya, Mas, and Raja, located in North Gorontalo Regency, have been designated as a nature reserve since the Dutch colonial era. These islands represent one of the world's best habitats for sea turtles, with four of the seven known species found there: the green turtle (*[Chelonia midas](/Green_sea_turtle)*), hawksbill turtle (*[Eretmochelys imbricata](/Hawksbill_sea_turtle)*), loggerhead turtle (*[Caretta caretta](/Caretta_caretta)*), and leatherback turtle (*[Dermochelys coriacea](/Dermochelys_coriacea)*). Sadly, in 2011, these vital nesting grounds were threatened by illegal poaching, fish bombing, and the destruction of coral reefs, a primary food source for turtles.

### Environment

The most pressing environmental issue plaguing Sulawesi is [deforestation](/Deforestation). By 2007, scientists estimated that 80% of Sulawesi's forest cover had been lost or severely degraded, with particular devastation in lowland areas and mangrove ecosystems. This rampant clearing, driven by logging and agricultural expansion, has placed many endemic species at critical risk. The island's wetlands have also suffered immensely, with a staggering 99% loss or damage. Beyond deforestation, bushmeat hunting and mining operations continue to exert pressure on the island's fragile environment.

#### Parks

Sulawesi hosts six national parks and nineteen nature reserves, complemented by three marine protected areas. Despite these designations, many of these vital conservation areas are under constant threat from logging, mining, and agricultural expansion, underscoring the ongoing struggle to protect the island's unique natural heritage.